## 3. Technical architecture

### 3.1 Data flow (end-to-end)
```
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ LAYER 1 — PUBLIC DATA (pulled once, cached locally)                  │
│   • NOAA ISD KPHX hourly temp 2019-2025   (no auth)                  │
│   • NREL NSRDB irradiance Phoenix (lat 33.45, lon -112.07) 2019-23   │
│   • EIA-930 hourly demand for AZPS balancing authority                │
│   • NREL ResStock AZ residential load profiles (15-min)              │
│   • NREL EVI-Pro Lite fleet load profiles (Phoenix climate zone)     │
│   • IEEE 123-bus feeder (.dss files from github.com/tshort/OpenDSS)   │
│   • HuggingFace EnergyBench (residential AMI substitute for Pecan St) │
└─────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                  │
                  ▼
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ LAYER 2 — FEATURE PIPELINE (ETL, CPU)                                │
│   Python/pandas. Outputs parquet at data/features/:                   │
│   • feeder_load_timeseries.parquet   (bus × time × kW/kVAR)           │
│   • weather_features.parquet         (T, T_lag1..24, GHI, humidity)   │
│   • calendar_features.parquet        (DoW, hour, holidays, heat-wave  │
│                                       flag: ≥3 consecutive days ≥110°)│
│   • topology.pt                      (PyG graph w/ line impedances)   │
└─────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                  │
                  ▼
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ LAYER 3 — MODELS (Colab Pro L4, driven via ml-trainer agent)         │
│   ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐             │
│   │  A. MTGNN  (hero graph model)                       │             │
│   │     — learns adjacency from load correlation        │             │
│   │     — outputs per-feeder point forecast, 24h @15min │             │
│   │     — weights: models/mtgnn_v1.pt                   │             │
│   │                                                     │             │
│   │  B. TFT    (quantile, pytorch-forecasting)          │             │
│   │     — per-feeder, known/unknown covariates          │             │
│   │     — outputs p10/p50/p90                           │             │
│   │     — weights: models/tft_v1.ckpt                   │             │
│   │                                                     │             │
│   │  C. DCRNN baseline (simple GNN for comparison)      │             │
│   │     — stretch goal                                  │             │
│   └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘             │
└─────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                  │   per-feeder p10/p50/p90 kW forecast
                  ▼
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ LAYER 4 — PHYSICS CHECK (OpenDSS, local CPU, ~sec/scenario)           │
│   For each horizon step t:                                            │
│     • write predicted kW/kVAR into OpenDSS Load objects               │
│     • Solution.Solve() → per-bus voltage, per-line loading            │
│     • flag voltage violations (ANSI C84.1 ±5%)                        │
│     • flag thermal violations (loading > 100% of line rating)         │
│   Outputs: risk_flags.parquet                                          │
└─────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                  │
                  ▼
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ LAYER 5 — DECISION ENGINE (Python rules + explainers)                 │
│   For each flagged feeder/time:                                       │
│     • extract TFT variable-importance → top 3 drivers                 │
│     • run GNNExplainer on MTGNN (stretch) → neighbour influence       │
│     • lookup rule book: load-transfer options (feeders ≤2 hops,       │
│       spare capacity from OpenDSS baseline), DR levers, battery       │
│       dispatch candidates                                             │
│     • emit ranked intervention list                                   │
└─────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                  │
                  ▼
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ LAYER 6 — DASHBOARD (Streamlit + pydeck, port 8501)                   │
│   • Map: pydeck ColumnLayer on feeder centroids, coloured by risk     │
│   • Click feeder → p10/p50/p90 ribbon, drivers, interventions         │
│   • Scenario panel: sliders for ΔT, EV%, PV% → live re-inference      │
│   • Metrics tab: reliability diagram, heat-wave vs normal split       │
│   • Export tab: CSV of feeder-upgrade ranking                         │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

### 3.2 Why MTGNN + TFT (vs. alternatives)

| Model | Pros | Cons | Decision |
|---|---|---|---|
| **MTGNN** (Graph WaveNet successor) | Learns adjacency end-to-end (critical — real feeder influence ≠ hand-drawn graph); strong on multi-variate time series; trains <1h on L4. | Research-quality code; no quantile head native. | **Hero** — handles the "spatio" well. |
| **Temporal Fusion Transformer** | Native quantile forecasts (p10/p50/p90); interpretable variable importance; handles static + dynamic + future-known covariates. | Per-series (not graph-native); heavier than LSTM. | **Ensemble partner** — handles the "temporal" + uncertainty. |
| DCRNN | Canonical baseline; simple to explain ("diffusion on the feeder graph"). | Static adjacency; weaker than MTGNN. | **Stretch baseline** (benchmark). |
| PatchTST | SOTA raw accuracy on many benchmarks. | No covariate story, no quantile head out-of-box, no graph. | **Skip.** |
| Foundation models (TimesFM-2, Chronos, Moirai) | Zero-shot baseline is a great demo plot ("we beat a foundation model"). | No graph, univariate-ish. | **Stretch** — zero-shot only. |
| PINN (full) | Physics-embedded. | Slow training, finicky. | **No** — use OpenDSS for physics check instead. |

**Final ensemble:** MTGNN → point forecast baseline; TFT → per-feeder quantile forecast + importance. Dashboard shows TFT p10/p50/p90 ribbon; physics check runs on MTGNN point output; flagged feeders get TFT variable importance in the sidebar.

### 3.3 Stack — exact versions

| Purpose | Package | Version | Why |
|---|---|---|---|
| DL framework | `torch` | 2.4+ | Stable, Colab-native. |
| Graph NN | `torch-geometric` | 2.6+ | MTGNN impl available. |
| Temporal GNN | `torch-geometric-temporal` | 0.55+ | DCRNN, AGCRN ready. |
| Forecasting | `pytorch-forecasting` | 1.4+ | TFT with quantile head. |
| Trainer | `pytorch-lightning` | 2.4+ | Clean checkpoint callbacks. |
| Power flow | `OpenDSSDirect.py` | 0.9.4+ | Prebuilt wheels for Ubuntu 24.04, no EPRI C++ build. |
| Dashboard | `streamlit` + `pydeck` + `plotly` | latest | 4-6 h build, judge-impressive. |
| Data wrangling | `pandas`, `polars`, `duckdb` | latest | DuckDB for S3 parquet filtering (ResStock). |
| Geospatial | `geopandas`, `shapely` | latest | feeder centroid map. |
| Cloud run | Colab Pro (L4) via `colab-mcp` | — | Training only. |
| Conformal | `mapie` | latest | Stretch: coverage guarantees. |
| Explainer | `torch-geometric` GNNExplainer | built-in | Stretch. |
| Weights hosting | git-lfs OR HuggingFace Hub | — | Pick by size (<200 MB → lfs). |

